  "learnings_before": "- Both valproate and carbamazepine are guideline‑consistent first‑line options for focal seizures in children ≤ 2 years; selection is guided by drug availability, tolerability, and the need for laboratory monitoring.\n- Aromatic AEDs (carbamazepine, lamotrigine, phenytoin) are acceptable for focal epilepsy but must be avoided in any child with a documented drug‑induced rash or hypersensitivity.\n- Before any change of therapy, clinicians must obtain baseline safety labs (ALT/AST < 2 × ULN, platelet count > 150 × 10⁹/L, ammonia within normal limits) and, when feasible, a serum level of the current AED.\n- Dose optimisation is performed first: if the current dose is < 20 mg/kg/day for valproate or < 15 mg/kg/day for carbamazepine and seizure control is suboptimal, the dose should be titrated upward in 25‑50 mg increments every 1–2 weeks before considering drug substitution or adjuncts.\n- Exaggerated startles, feeding difficulty, or increased tone in children with cerebral palsy are not automatically attributed to drug toxicity; they require confirmation (e.g., seizure diary or video‑EEG) before altering the regimen.\n- The decision hierarchy is: (1) confirm seizure‑free status (≥ 6 months) and adherence ≥ 80 %; (2) verify normal safety labs; (3) maintain the current regimen unchanged; (4) if either seizure control or labs are inadequate, proceed to dose optimisation; (5) if optimisation fails, consider switching to valproate (after normal LFTs) or adding levetiracetam as an adjunct.\n- Valproate is stocked in >90 % of district pharmacies at ≈ $0.08 per 100 mg; carbamazepine is similarly stocked at ≈ $0.05 per 100 mg; levetiracetam is 2–3 × more expensive and often unavailable, so it is reserved for documented valproate intolerance or failure.\n- Phenobarbital is reserved for refractory cases or when both valproate and levetiracetam are unavailable; it may be used in spastic cerebral palsy only with close monitoring for sedation, otherwise it is avoided.\n- Initiation of valproate requires baseline liver function tests and ammonia; if ALT/AST > 2 × ULN or ammonia is elevated, valproate should be deferred and an alternative AED chosen.\n- When a child is seizure‑free on a stable valproate dose within the therapeutic window (20–30 mg/kg/day) and safety labs are normal, the protocol mandates continuation of the exact current dose without escalation or adjunct addition.",
  "candidate_learnings": "- Valproate is the primary first‑line AED for generalized epilepsies, but dose should not exceed 20 mg/kg/day without confirmed therapeutic monitoring; when this ceiling is reached and labs are normal, the regimen is maintained.\n- In children with Doße (myoclonic‑atonic) syndrome, the preferred regimen is valproate combined with lamotrigine; lamotrigine is initiated at 0.5 mg/kg/day and titrated slowly (0.5 mg/kg/week for two weeks, then 1 mg/kg/week) to a maximum of 3–5 mg/kg/day when co‑administered with valproate, with weekly rash checks and baseline/interval CBC/LFTs.\n- Ethosuximide is reserved for pure absence seizures and only considered when the drug is stocked locally; it is a lower priority adjunct in Doße syndrome due to limited efficacy for myoclonic‑atonic seizures.\n- All dose recommendations must be expressed in whole tablet units that match available formulations (e.g., valproate 250 mg tablets, lamotrigine 100 mg tablets); doses that fall between tablet strengths are rounded to the nearest feasible amount and documented.\n- Laboratory monitoring is mandatory before any dose change: baseline ALT/AST, ammonia, and CBC must be documented as normal; after each valproate increase repeat LFTs and ammonia one week later, after each lamotrigine titration repeat CBC/LFTs after the first two increments, and after levetiracetam escalation obtain renal function before change and repeat two weeks later.\n- Adjunctive therapy (e.g., levetiracetam) is introduced only after documented breakthrough seizures despite therapeutic valproate levels or documented intolerance to valproate; behavioral side‑effects such as irritability or aggression are monitored with caregiver questionnaires, and dose adjustments are made if significant.\n- Phenobarbital is contraindicated for infantile spasms and Doße syndrome in children under 12 months; it is used only as a last‑resort rescue when first‑line agents are unavailable or ineffective, due to its sedation and developmental toxicity.\n- Drug selection follows a cost‑availability hierarchy: prioritize agents that are stocked in >80 % of district pharmacies and have the lowest unit cost (e.g., carbamazepine ≈ $0.05/100 mg, valproate ≈ $0.08/100 mg, lamotrigine ≈ $0.06/100 mg); more expensive or rarely stocked drugs such as levetiracetam and ethosuximide are used only when cheaper first‑line options are unsuitable.\n- When two first‑line agents are clinically equivalent, the drug with higher local availability and lower price is chosen.\n- For refractory cases after maximal optimisation of valproate + lamotrigine ± levetiracetam, consider non‑pharmacologic options such as ketogenic diet (if caregiver capacity permits) and referral to a tertiary epilepsy centre for possible surgical evaluation.\n- Decision‑making follows a linear flow: verify labs and adherence → assess seizure‑free period (≥ 3 months) → maintain current dose if within therapeutic range → titrate current AED if sub‑therapeutic → add lamotrigine for myoclonic‑atonic dominance → consider levetiracetam only after confirmed valproate intolerance or failure → resort to ethosuxide only for pure absence seizures and when stocked → employ phenobarbital or ketogenic diet as last‑line measures.\n- Patient‑specific factors heavily influence drug choice: malnutrition or anemia must be corrected before aggressive dose escalation; cerebral palsy increases risk of hepatic toxicity with valproate, nudging clinicians toward carbamazepine or lamotrigine when appropriate.\n- Accurate phenotyping of seizure type is essential: if myoclonic‑atonic seizures constitute ≥ 50 % of events, prioritize valproate + lamotrigine; if absence seizures dominate, ethosuximide becomes the preferred adjunct, provided it is available.",
